🔢 LeetCode 261 — Graph Valid Tree
📌 Problem Statement
Given n nodes labeled from 0 to n - 1 and a list of undirected edges, determine whether these edges form a valid tree.
You are given:
An integer n → number of nodes
A 2D array edges where edges[i] = [a, b] means there is an undirected edge between node a and node b.
Your task is to return true if the graph forms a valid tree, otherwise return false.
🌳 What is a Valid Tree?
A graph is a valid tree if:
1️⃣ It is connected :- Every node can be reached from any other node.
2️⃣ It has no cycles :- There is no path that starts and ends at the same node.
3️⃣ Number of edges = n - 1

For a tree with n nodes: edges=n-1
If edges > n-1 → there must be a cycle
🧾 Example 1
Input:
n = 5
edges = [[0,1],[0,2],[0,3],[1,4]]

Output:
true

Explanation:

    0
  / | \
 1  2  3
 |
 4

No cycle

All nodes connected

Edges = 4 = n - 1

✅ This is a valid tree

public boolean validTree(int n, int[][] edges) {
    // A tree MUST have exactly n-1 edges
    if (edges.length != n - 1) return false;

    // Build adjacency list
    List<List<Integer>> adj = new ArrayList<>();
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) adj.add(new ArrayList<>());
    for (int[] e : edges) {
        adj.get(e[0]).add(e[1]);
        adj.get(e[1]).add(e[0]);
    }

    // BFS from node 0 — count reachable nodes
    boolean[] visited = new boolean[n];
    Queue<Integer> queue = new LinkedList<>();
    queue.offer(0);  visited[0] = true;
    int count = 0;
    while (!queue.isEmpty()) {
        int node = queue.poll();  count++;
        for (int nbr : adj.get(node)) {
            if (!visited[nbr]) {
                visited[nbr] = true;
                queue.offer(nbr);
            }
        }
    }
    return count == n;  // all nodes reachable?
}
// Time: O(V+E)  |  Space: O(V+E)


